         <abstract>
            <p>Finite-difference methods for parabolic initial boundary problems are usually treated as marching procedures. However, if the solution reaches a known steady state value as t → ∞, one may provide approximate values on a line t = T for a preselected T suitably large. With this extra data, it is feasible to consider the use of elliptic boundary-value techniques for the numerical computation of such problems. In this report we give a complete analysis of this method for the linear second-order case with time-independent coefficients. We also discuss iterative methods for solving the difference equations. Finally, we give an example where the method fails.</p>
          </abstract>
